<Base title="Lurking, Aesthetic of Withdrawal and Y2K — Michalina Sablik">
  <div class="container page-content">
    <h1>Lurking, Aesthetic of Withdrawal and Y2K. On Laureta Hajrullahu's Practice</h1>
    <p class="exhibition-detail-venue">Curatorial essay | "to undo, to crumble, to vanish" — National Gallery of Kosovo, 2026</p>
    <div class="exhibition-detail-body">
      <p>The essay discusses contemporary gaming aesthetics focused on "walking simulators" and non-violent gameplay, examining how these stripped-down digital environments offer an alternative to the hyper-competitive logic of mainstream gaming culture.</p>
      <p>Central to the text is the concept of the "aesthetics of withdrawal" as a form of artistic and political resistance — a deliberate stepping-back from the demands of visibility, productivity, and constant self-presentation.</p>
      <p>The essay explores online lurking as strategic invisibility against surveillance capitalism, arguing that the refusal to participate, to post, to engage, constitutes a meaningful act of resistance in an attention economy.</p>
      <p>Drawing on Object-Oriented Ontology, the text considers non-human perspectives in digital spaces, questioning the primacy of human experience in virtual environments.</p>
      <p>Hajrullahu's installation features oversized pixelated stone-like objects with projected holograms. Her video work "That Which Gave Chase" presents a trapped protagonist navigating game-like spaces, caught between agency and confinement.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
